Born to an always-ambitious, mid-western upstart, Grant seemed however naïve, if not reluctant, on matters of business.
As Chernow describes, “A certified failure in civilian life, Grant had entered the war with everything to gain and nothing to lose.
Writing in September 1879, Walt Whitman summarizes Grant’s life, while lodging it in a historic genre:“Cynical critics .
In Grant, the “best of us” people have not a model, but an inspiration, a reassertion, a story of redemption.